🔥 FACTORY METHOD PATTERN — EASY + INTERESTING NOTES (INTERFACE VERSION)
---
🎯 1. THE REAL PROBLEM
---

Imagine you are writing this in your service:
```
new EmailNotification()
```

Looks simple… but 😬
Problems:

* Service directly depends on Email/SMS classes ❌
* Adding new type → you must MODIFY service ❌
* Code becomes messy with if-else ❌

👉 This is called **tight coupling**

---
💡 2. CORE IDEA (THE BIG SHIFT)
---
Instead of:
```
Service → creates object ❌
```

We do:
```
Service → “Factory, give me the object” ✅
```
👉 Service only USES
👉 Factory CREATES
Clean separation of responsibility.

---
🧱 3. KEY COMPONENTS (THINK IN ROLES)
---

1️⃣ PRODUCT (Interface) → “WHAT to do”

```
interface Notification {
    void send();
}
```
🧠 Think:
“Every notification must be able to send”

---
2️⃣ CONCRETE PRODUCTS → “HOW it works”

```
EmailNotification → sends email 📧
SMSNotification → sends SMS 📱
```

🧠 Think:
Same method → different behavior

---
3️⃣ FACTORY (Interface) → “HOW to create”

```
interface NotificationFactory {
    Notification createNotification();
}
```

🧠 Think:
“Give me a notification, I don’t care which one”

---
4️⃣ CONCRETE FACTORIES → “Actual creators”

```
EmailFactory → creates EmailNotification
SMSFactory → creates SMSNotification
```

🧠 Think:
“I only create my specific type”

---
5️⃣ SERVICE → “WHEN to use”

👉 Uses notification
👉 Does NOT create it

🧠 Think:
“I just use it, I don’t build it”

---
6️⃣ CLIENT (Main) → “WHAT to choose”

👉 Decides:
Email / SMS / Push?

---
🔄 4. FLOW (LIKE A STORY 🎬)
---

Main:
👉 “I want Email”

↓
Creates EmailFactory

↓
Passes it to Service

↓
Service says:
👉 “Factory, give me a notification”

↓
Factory says:
👉 “Here is EmailNotification”

↓
Service calls:
👉 send()

↓
Output:
👉 "Email sent" 📧

---
🧠 5. MENTAL MODEL (VERY IMPORTANT)
---

Think like this:

Client → chooses TYPE
Factory → creates OBJECT
Service → uses OBJECT
Product → does WORK

---
⚔️ 6. BEFORE vs AFTER
---

❌ WITHOUT FACTORY

```
if(type == EMAIL)
    new EmailNotification()

if(type == SMS)
    new SMSNotification()
```

Problems:

* if-else everywhere 😵
* Must modify code every time

---

✅ WITH FACTORY

```
Notification n = factory.createNotification();
n.send();
```

Benefits:

* Clean code ✨
* No if-else 🚫
* Easy to extend 🚀

---
🔗 7. HOW TIGHT COUPLING IS REMOVED
---

Before:
Service → EmailNotification ❌

After:
Service → Notification (interface) ✅

👉 Service does NOT know:

* Email?
* SMS?
* Push?

👉 It only knows:
“Call send()”

---
➕ 8. ADDING NEW TYPE (Push Notification)
---

Just add:

1. PushNotification implements Notification
2. PushFactory implements NotificationFactory

Change only in Main:

```
factory = new PushFactory();
```

---
❗ WHAT YOU DID NOT TOUCH:

* Service ✅
* Existing code ✅
* Old factories ✅

👉 That’s Open/Closed Principle 🔥

---
🚀 9. WHY THIS PATTERN EXISTS
---

Because we want:

✔ Loose coupling
✔ Clean architecture
✔ Easy extensibility
✔ Scalable systems

---
⚖️ 10. TRADE-OFF
---

❌ Cons:

* More classes 😅
* Slightly complex at first

✅ Pros:

* Maintainable
* Flexible
* Industry-grade design

👉 Short-term complexity, long-term clarity 💪

---
🎯 11. ONE-LINE SUMMARY
---

Factory Method =
👉 “Move object creation out of service into a factory”

---
🧠 12. FINAL MEMORY TRICK
---

❌ Old way:

```
Service → new Object()
```

✅ Factory way:

```
Service → Factory → Object
```

